<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / International Capital Markets: More Russian licences given
to foreign banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO more western banks yesterday received licences to set up subsidiaries in
Russia as the Russian central bank attempted to head off a plan by
parliament to ban foreign banks from dealing with Russian customers.
Western bankers said that the central bank had confirmed general banking
licences for Credit Suisse and the Netherlands' ING Bank. This extends to
six the number of banks that have received permission to start operations in
Russia.
On Friday, parliament is due to decide whether to confirm a resolution
confining foreign banks to dealing with foreign clients from 1994 to 1996.
Mr Viktor Gerashchenko, the central bank chairman, is thought to be trying
to present parliament with a fait accompli by giving licences to as many
foreign banks as possible before parliament takes a decision reversing the
terms of the licences.
Banque Indosuez is to close its Japanese share broking operations in Tokyo,
Reuter reports from Tokyo. This follows an earlier decision to shut its
Indosuez Capital Securities operation in London.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Credit Suisse.
    Internationale Nederlanden Groep.
    Banque Indosuez.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Patents &amp; Licences.
