<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / International Company News: Foster's moves back into the
black at six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOSTER'S Brewing, the Australian brewing group with substantial operations
in the UK and Canada, yesterday returned to the black with a ADollars 310m
(USDollars 201m) profit after tax and abnormal items for the year ended
June.
The figure compares with a ADollars 950.8m loss in the previous year, a
result that was largely due to asset write-offs and other one-off charges.
At the operating profit level, before both tax and abnormal items, Foster's
reported a profit of ADollars 279.5m for the year just ended, up by 5.7 per
cent on last time's ADollars 264.4m.
Nevertheless, Foster's - which saw a management shake-up earlier this year
and in which Broken Hill Proprietary acquired a sizeable minority stake last
year - said that it was pleased with the results 'in the light of subdued
economic conditions and continuing declines in beer industry volumes in
Australia, the UK and Canada'.
Profit from the core brewing operations actually fell over the year, by
about ADollars 28m to ADollars 527m. Carlton and United Breweries posted an
11 per cent increase in operating earnings at ADollars 211m, with gains in
both volume and market share.
However, the Courage interests in the UK saw operating earnings fall to
ADollars 208 from ADollars 244m - although the fall was largely explained by
a resumption of contributions to the Courage Pension Funds, absorbing
ADollars 35m. Inntrepreneur Estates was described as 'trading
satisfactorily' with reduced losses.
Meanwhile, the profit contribution from Canada's Molson Breweries declined
to ADollars 107m from ADollars 120m - although Foster's blamed much of the
shortfall on the one-time cost of retaliatory duties on products exported to
the US and a reduced contribution in the final three months following the
sale of a 10 per cent interest in Molson to Philip Morris's Miller Brewing
division.
Interest expense was significantly reduced to ADollars 206m, compared with
ADollars 249.7m last time, due to the equity raising last year and a spate
of non-core asset sales.
Foster's said that these produced cash inflows of ADollars 648m, ahead of
budget, and that the disposal programme would continue for the next two to
four years.
The bottom-line profits figure was also aided by a ADollars 46m surplus on
abnormal items, stemming mainly from the profit on the sale of the Molson
shares.
Looking ahead, Foster's said it was not anticipating any significant
short-term improvement in beer industry volumes in the group's main markets
but it would continue to focus on non-core asset sales, debt reduction and
pushing down costs.
</TEXT>
