<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Raw material costs limit growth at British
Polythene
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAW MATERIAL increases adversely affected British Polythene Industries, the
acquisitive polythene film products maker, which reported slightly increased
pre-tax profits up from Pounds 6.53m to Pounds 6.61m in the half year to
June 30.
Operating profits slipped from from Pounds 7.81m to Pounds 7.77m on
increased sales of Pounds 96.6m (Pounds 85.1m).
The group has bought three businesses since it raised Pounds 20.6m earlier
this year in a rights issue, taking total acquisitions to 11 since its
Pounds 15.5m rights issue in 1991.
However, Mr Cameron McLatchie, chairman and chief executive, expects the
company's rate of acquisitions to slow down.
'Target companies are attracting higher prices than we believe are
justified. We are not willing to pay the prices that people seem to be
paying and will therefore wait until the market is more favourable.'
Mr McLatchie said the three businesses purchased since March were operating
profitably. The company is not planning to manufacture retail bags in a
joint venture in China until next year.
Borrowings rose to Pounds 14m (Pounds 12.5m), mainly because of
acquisitions, representing gearing of 18 per cent. Lower interest rates saw
a decline in net interest payable to Pounds 698,000 (Pounds 771,000).
Fully diluted earnings per share fell to 12.29p (13.27p). The interim
dividend is increased to 3.75p (3.5p).
