<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Huntsman-Packer venture buys Texaco chemicals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEXACO, the US oil group, yesterday sold of most of its chemical operations
for Dollars 1.06bn (Pounds 680m) as part of the restructuring of the
petrochemicals industry in Europe and the US.
The business is being acquired by a joint venture between Huntsman Financial
Corporation, a subsidiary of Huntsman group, the US's biggest private
chemical company, and Consolidated Press Holdings, Mr Kerry Packer's
Sydney-based media and investment group.
Huntsman Corporation, the 50-50 venture, will be managed by Mr Jon Huntsman,
the chief executive and founder of Huntsman Financial Corporation, and his
family.
Mr Huntsman said the deal showed his and Mr Packer's determination to expand
their global chemical operations. Last year the companies jointly acquired
the Chemplex petrochemical complexes in Melbourne, Australia. The deal
boosts the annual revenues of the Huntsman companies from Dollars 1.8bn to
more than Dollars 3.1bn.
Huntsman also announced it was acquiring the expandable polystyrene
operations of Elf Atochem at Ribecourt in north-east France for an
undisclosed sum. The plant has an annual capacity of about 75,000 tonnes,
although it is operating at only 52,000 tonnes a year because of
overcapacity in the European market. The business had a turnover last year
of more than FFr400m (Pounds 45m).
In a separate deal, Elf Atochem announced it was acquiring the French low
density polyethylene activities of Enichem, the troubled Italian group. The
plant, attached to Elf Atochem's petrochemical facilities at Carling
Saint-Avold in eastern France, has a capacity of 210,000 tonnes a year and a
turnover of about FFr900m. Terms were not disclosed.
Texaco's chemicals operations generated a trading loss of Dollars 49m last
year on turnover of Dollars 1.4bn. The business acquired by Huntsman
Corporation employs more than 2,600 employees and almost 2,500 contractors.
It includes six plants in the US, as well as facilities in Canada, Belgium,
Brazil, Colombia and the UK.
The Huntsman-Texaco deal includes an option for Huntsman Corporation to
acquire either half or all of Texaco's giant Dollars 400m plant at Port
Neches, Texas.
Details, Page 24
