<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / AEA smoothes way for sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AEA Technology, formerly the UK Atomic Energy Authority, has announced
reorganisation plans which could help smooth its path towards privatisation.
AEA has told its 8,000 staff that, from next April, it is to divide its
activities into three separate divisions to differentiate more clearly
between core businesses.
Staff have already been told that the workforce will fall to around 7,500 by
next March. A spokesman said yesterday that the reorganisation could lead to
a further reduction in employee numbers.
No details of job losses are yet available but the company has said it hopes
any redundancies can be made on a voluntary basis.
Under the structure AEA will run a commercial division, which it hopes will
provide the basis for any sell-off, and a government division which will
continue to handle all government nuclear installations and liabilities.
There will also be a services division.
The changes follow an analysis of AEA's activities undertaken as part of the
company's representations to the government on privatisation. Ministers
commissioned their own report on moving AEA into the private sector in
April.
Sir Anthony Cleaver, AEA chairman, said the changes were 'logical and,
indeed, essential to securing AEA's successful future'.
