<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / DSS may cushion water charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL SECURITY may help cushion poorer households if the installation of
water meters pushes up their bills, Mr Tim Yeo, environment minister, said
yesterday.
Controversy about the impact of metering is set to increase after the
publication yesterday of the results of three-year trials of water meters in
England and Wales. Ofwat and the National Rivers Authority, the industry
regulators, have joined the government in backing an extension of metering
as a way of charging customers.
Most households now pay a flat annual fee based on property value under the
old rating system, but water companies must find a new basis for charging by
the year 2000. Some households are likely to pay less if meters are
installed - including pensioners living alone, one sixth of the total,
according to Mr Yeo.
However large families will probably pay more. Ms Janet Langdon, director of
the Water Services Association, which represents the 10 large water and
sewerage companies said: 'We think it is essential that the social security
system provides some support for those households who can't pay their bill'.
The largest water meter trial, in the Isle of Wight, covering 50,000
households, suggested that they used 21 per cent less water after a meter
was fitted. However 11 smaller trials, covering some 10,000 households,
found an average drop of only 11 per cent compared with similar unmetered
areas.
The report also concluded that installation and running costs were high. The
Isle of Wight trial suggested the running costs of a metered system were on
average Pounds 19.08 a year higher than a system based on rateable values.
</TEXT>
