FT  14 SEP 93 / Tories deny banking favours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL BANK of Scotland yesterday leapt to the defence of the Conservative
party after Labour sought an assurance that the bank was not giving the
organisation preferential treatment over its overdraft, Alison Smith writes.
Both the bank and Conservative Central Office said that the Tory party was
being charged a commercial rate.
The financial report in the Conservative party conference agenda, which was
published yesterday, said that the revenue deficit was Pounds 18.6m, but
that a small surplus was hoped for this year.
There was a fall, however, in the payments that constituencies were supposed
to make, and these quota payments totalled only Pounds 1.23m compared with
Pounds 1.44m the previous year.
Earlier yesterday Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory party chairman, said that
substantial progress had been made in putting the party's finances on a
sounder footing.
Royal Bank's statement came after Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade and
industry secretary, demanded that the bank justify or change its treatment
of the Tories.
