<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Bath: a beautiful city of burglars and beggars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, WALES and WEST CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAFFIC POLLUTION, aggressive beggars, drunken gangs, ram raiders, empty
shops . . . this could be one of Britain's more deprived urban areas. But it
is Bath, a genteel Georgian city and world heritage site attracting 2m
visitors a year, as depicted in a 'city centre audit'.
The audit is by Ms Kimberly Paumier, appointed manager of the city centre in
April to help revitalise it. An American, she is described by Bath's chief
executive, Mr Clive Abbott, as someone who is 'able to take a fresh and
critical view'.
Ms Paumier's first report, which went to Bath council's environment
committee yesterday, says that 'Bath is a beautiful city, gifted with
resources and assets not found in most UK cities'. It also praises the Roman
and Georgian architecture, the quality of the shops and culture - there are
17 museums.
However, the report also points to poor road connections and congested
streets, high levels of pollution and a scruffy railway station.
Although the city is described as one of Britain's top retail locations, Ms
Paumier says a perception that rates and rents are higher than elsewhere has
increased the number of vacant shops. For retailers who remain in business,
ram-raiding is a significant problem and the council is to consider
closed-circuit television.
The report highlights concern over drunks and travellers causing tension and
animosity. Ms Paumier welcomes busking and street theatre as assets for
Bath, but 'the amount of aggressive begging is a growing threat', she says.
Ms Paumier adds: 'Bath after dark can sometimes be a threatening place' with
large groups of 'often drunk or disruptive' youths. The police, 'tend to
stay at a distance for fear that they might incite further aggression'.
Among Ms Paumier's proposals are a leisure and health spa to encourage
overnight stays by visitors, more conference facilities and greater use of
the river Avon.
</TEXT>
<XX>
