<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Councils hit at plan to expand Heathrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS TO construct a Pounds 800m-Pounds 900m fifth terminal at London's
Heathrow airport, and government proposals to increase the number of night
flights, have led to fierce opposition from local authorities near the
world's busiest international airport.
The London Borough of Hounslow yesterday voted against the expansion
proposals, arguing that the plans put forward by BAA, the privatised
airports operator, would create unacceptable increases in road traffic,
aircraft noise, night flights and pollution. It said there would also be
pressure for the construction of a third runway at Heathrow.
'The economic benefits of Terminal Five are outweighed by the disadvantages
of the massive new development,' said Mr Bob Whatley, a Hounslow councillor.
BAA is anxious to develop a fifth terminal to meet future air-travel demand
at the already congested airport and to fend off other European competitors
such as Paris, Amsterdam and Frankfurt which are seeking to challenge
Heathrow's role as an international hub.
Hounslow is the first of a number of London local authorities getting ready
to fight a planning inquiry into the new terminal project which is due to
start in 1995.
The Hounslow move also coincides with a challenge by local authorities
around Heathrow against government proposals to change night-flight
regulations at the airport.
The local authorities, including Richmond, Windsor and Maidenhead,
Hillingdon, Hounslow, and Slough, have won a judicial review of the
government proposals.
The government is planning to introduce a new quota system for night flights
based on the noise performance of aircraft, replacing the system based on a
specific number of aircraft movements.
The local authorities say that the new system would increase the overall
number of night flights and cause more disturbance for local residents.
</TEXT>
