<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Building costs set to rise: Contractors will pass on
materials price increases, RICS says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION costs could rise by nearly 4 per cent next year because
contractors are no longer able to absorb the rising price of building
materials, according to a Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors survey
published today.
Contractors face growing pressure as increases in materials prices eat away
profit margins, said the institution in its quarterly study of building
costs.
'Over the next two years, the price of materials is expected to rise above
the general rate of inflation,' said Mr Christopher Vickers, the
institution's construction spokesman.
'As a result the bubble will burst and contractors, unable to absorb rising
costs, will be forced to increase their bids for tender.'
The study highlights an issue of growing concern for building contractors.
Building materials prices fell steeply in the early 1990s, but have recently
begun to rise again.
Throughout the recession, intense competition in the construction industry
has forced tender prices down, and contractors have had little or no hope of
passing rises in materials prices on to customers. Subcontractors,
meanwhile, have complained that larger contractors have been delaying
payments to them.
The institution's survey showed that tender prices have stabilised at
early-1987 levels, ending three years of decline. The cost of building is 23
per cent lower than the peak levels recorded in 1989.
The institution said tender prices were unchanged in the second quarter of
this year, compared with the previous quarter, and expected them to hold
steady until the first quarter of next year.
Then, however, increasing material and wage costs would prompt a resurgence
of tender price inflation. By the fourth quarter tender prices would be
nearly 4 per cent higher than in the fourth quarter of this year.
The institution said building material prices were expected to rise 5.3 per
cent in the 12 months to the third quarter of 1994, followed by a further
5.5 per cent increase in the 12 months after that.
In line with other industry forecasts, the institution said that
construction output would continue to decline, but grow by 1 per cent in
1994, 'progressing gradually' in 1995.
Although this is a modest rate of recovery, it would at least give
contractors more hope of passing on materials increases to customers than
they have at present.
Building Cost Information Service quarterly review. Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors, 85/87 Clarence Street, Kingston, Surrey KT1 1RB. Pounds
50, or Pounds 160 per year.
</TEXT>
