<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Local authorities granted easing of tendering rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITIES will be exempt from the government's new regulations on
compulsory competitive tendering for white-collar services if they have
already conducted a market test, the government said yesterday.
This relaxation of the tendering rules, announced by the local government
minister, Mr David Curry, was welcomed by local authorities. The Association
of County Councils said that many councils had already opened their
professional services to competition without the need for the government to
make such moves compulsory.
The Association of District Councils also welcomed the move, but called on
the government to announce the full compulsory rules for white-collar
tendering as soon as possible.
It said that otherwise there was a risk that councils could go to great
expense on market testing exercises, and then have to repeat them when new
regulations were announced.
Under the concessions announced by Mr Curry, councils will be exempt from
compulsory tendering of work for up to five years if contracts for the work
have been awarded after they had attracted at least three tenders from
external contractors, as well as from the council's direct service
organisations.
Authorities that have failed to meet this criterion but believe their
contracts have been adequately tested against the market are able to apply
to the Department of the Environment for the exemption.
Councils needed to have attracted the three tenders by yesterday to qualify
for the exemption. Councils which have not yet done so will be required to
go through the formal tendering process already outlined in existing
legislation.
</TEXT>
