<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Lloyd's may seek market cash to settle writs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF LONDON may ask the agencies that manage syndicates at the market
and brokers who trade there to make financial contributions to help settle
long-running litigation involving Names.
Mr Peter Middleton, chief executive, said that Lloyd's 'might well come to
the conclusion that the chairman should invite people in the market to
contribute to a fund if this made a settlement possible'.
Money to settle legal actions involving several thousand Names - the
individuals who pledge their wealth to back the market - could also come
from two other sources: errors and omissions insurers, which insure agencies
against legal awards for negligence, and the Lloyd's central fund, which
meets claims when Names are unable to fulfil their obligations.
'If we come to the point where we need some money in addition I'm confident
that the chairman will be able to persuade the market that we need their
help,' said Mr Middleton, adding that he was now more confident about a
settlement than he had been three months ago.
Last year efforts to persuade agencies and brokers to contribute to a Pounds
50m hardship fund for stricken Names were unsuccessful. This failure was
partially because Lloyd's failed in its efforts to secure charitable status
for the proposed scheme.
But Mr Middleton said the scheme had failed because 'the old Lloyd's people
made public pronouncements before they had done their homework'.
Sir Jeremy Morse, former chairman of Lloyds Bank, who heads a Lloyd's panel
examining the financial resources available for a settlement, would be
involved in any market appeal.
Figures published yesterday in Lloyd's guide to corporate membership showed
the extent to which the central fund has been stretched by recent claims.
At 31 August the amount 'earmarked' from the central fund to meet claims
that Names have not yet paid or may be unable to pay amounted to Pounds
1.195bn, briefly in excess of the fund's Pounds 1bn, compared to Pounds 636m
at the same time last year and Pounds 200m in 1991.
The amount of funds 'earmarked' typically declines as Names meet calls upon
them.
By the end of last year the amount 'earmarked' had fallen to Pounds 354.9m,
for example. Lloyd's has other assets which can be matched against these
liabilities.
The guide also shows that overall net assets available to the society of
Lloyd's have declined in recent years. By the end of 1992 these amounted to
Pounds 6.091bn, compared with Pounds 6.537bn at the end of 1991.
</TEXT>
