<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Britannia to buy Dutch life arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITANNIA, the UK's ninth largest building society, is to buy Life
Association of Scotland, the UK life-insurance subsidiary of the Dutch-based
Internationale Nederlanden Group, Norma Cohen writes.
The move is part of a growing trend in banks and building societies to
purchase their own life-insurance subsidiaries and sell their products
through their branches.
Mr John Heaps, Britannia managing director, said it intends to inject about
Pounds 25m into its new subsidiary over the next two years. Britannia will
sell LAS products both through its 250 branches and through independent
financial advisers.
The direct sales operation will be integrated into Britannia's existing
sales force.
Britannia is the largest building society retailing its own
financial-services products with Pounds 2.5bn in assets under management.
LAS has Pounds 950m in assets under management.
