<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Israel and the PLO: Israel sounds note of caution on future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR YITZHAK RABIN, Israel's prime minister, last night delivered a markedly
sober assessment of the next stages of negotiation with the Palestine
Liberation Organisation, just hours after the emotionally-charged signing
ceremony with the PLO at the White House.
In a joint press conference with Mr Shimon Peres, his foreign minister, Mr
Rabin laid out Israel's conditions during the installation of an interim
period of Palestinian rule in the West Bank and Gaza strip, while issuing a
challenge to the international community to back peace - notably the Gulf
states.
A tired-looking Mr Rabin also acknowledged the commitments made by Mr Yassir
Arafat, the PLO leader, which enabled Israeli recognition of the
organisation. But he said it would represent a change from the past only if
the PLO meets these conditions. 'I believe it's a change if the commitments
will be fulfilled,' he told reporters. 'We have decided to take a chance, to
put him into a test.'
Mr Rabin said Israel would insist on several 'key issues' during the next
round of discussions with the PLO. He said 'united Jerusalem must remain
united under Israel's sovereignty and our capital forever,' adding that the
issue of Jerusalem's status could nevertheless be discussed in negotiations
towards a final settlement. 'They are allowed to raise it,' he said.
He also said he wanted no existing Israeli settlements to be uprooted. In
addition, Israel would insist on keeping full responsibility for all
Israelis in settlements in Gaza and the West Bank. 'None of them (the
settlers) will come under the authority of the Palestinians in the council,'
he said, referring to the authority to be elected in nine months of the
start of the declaration of principles signed yesterday.
Mr Rabin also sketched a sombre picture of the economic needs of the West
Bank and, particularly Gaza, where he said: 'All the miseries - you can find
there.' He said Israel already spent Dollars 350m (Pounds 227m) a year on
basic needs there, but said international aid would be necessary to make
peace work.
In a direct appeal to the Gulf states, whose relations with the PLO have
been icy since Mr Arafat's pro-Iraqi stand in the Gulf war, he said: 'Will
the world, which speaks so much about peace, will it be ready to take even
more than that?' Then he added: 'It can be done,' he added. 'It depends on
the realisation of the Arab rich countries who don't like Arafat . . . at
least to give money to the territories.'
In what had become a downbeat coda to the sunlit euphoria of the morning
signing, Mr Rabin said: 'If we do not create a hope, a real one that is
based on realities to the Gazans, that as a result of this agreement their
conditions will be improved - I don't know if this whole ceremony will lead
to a solution.'
</TEXT>
