<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / World Trade News: Spain backs France on farm trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Leon Brittan, EC commissioner in charge of trade, yesterday held
meetings in Washington designed to avert a new round of transatlantic trade
hostilities.
His visit to Washington, where he will receive an award, comes in the wake
of a formal diplomatic protest, delivered by US officials on Friday in
Brussels. They warned that French demands to reopen the Blair House accord
on farm trade, reached last year, could undermine the entire pact.
However, Spain yesterday backed France's opposition to the Blair House
accord, in effect threatening its own veto on this vital building-block for
concluding the Uruguay Round world trade reform talks.
In a memorandum to the European Commission and Spain's EC partners, Mr
Javier Gomez Navarro, the Spanish trade minister, called for a series of
modifications to Blair House which echo some of the main French demands.
The pact's provisions on oilseeds last year averted a trade war, during
which the US was threatening sanctions against EC trade worth up to Dollars
1bn (Pounds 650m). US farm interests believe they made great concessions on
oilseeds in order to get a barely acceptable Uruguay Round deal covering
agriculture.
Spain, like France, wants the 21 per cent cut in subsidised food exports to
be spread over longer than six years; to exclude from these cuts added value
food products, food aid, and current EC food stockpiles; and for the cuts to
fall on sectors rather than individual products, thereby allowing the EC to
export more in areas where it either earns most or is most competitive.
</TEXT>
