<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Hungary reveals banking fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CRIMINAL inquiries into Hungarian banks have uncovered Dollars 170m (Pounds
110m) to Dollars 190m of losses due to fraud, negligence, bribery and other
offences, the chief prosecutor's office has announced.
Under investigation are 42 cases covering the spectrum of financial crime.
In several instances, bank managers are alleged to have accepted bribes to
underscore credit risk, overlook fake security, or grant preferential loans.
In the largest single case, the authorities are taking action against the
management of Ybl Bank, a private bank, which collapsed last year, for
misuse of Ft6bn (Pounds 41m) of deposits.
Explaining the proliferation of corruption, Mr Ivan Szabo, the Hungarian
finance minister, blamed the spread of the black economy, which some
estimates put at 25 per cent of gross domestic product.
Most of the cases are old ones which have simply taken time to work their
way through a creaky legal system, officials emphasise, and they have
downplayed the significance of bank corruption.
The latest burst of media interest in the problems of Hungarian banks comes
as a World Bank delegation is in Budapest to consider help for a financial
sector laden with bad loans.
Nevertheless, the Budapest authorities remain confident that the World Bank
will grant a loan of Dollars 200m-Dollars 300m to help recapitalise
Hungary's commercial banks. A World Bank report earlier this year found some
banks 'technically insolvent according to international accounting
standards'.
Bankers pointed out that a more significant problem for banks, though not a
legal one, is represented by discretionary lending by local bank managers:
central reporting systems are only now being introduced.
The inquiries into bank fraud have contributed to increasing public
suspicion that corruption is widespread.
</TEXT>
