<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Norwegian Election: EC issue sways Norway vote - Labour
party set to remain in power as minority government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY'S Labour party last night tightened its hold on power as a minority
government after increasing its vote in the general election. But with 89
per cent of the votes counted, results also showed strong resistance to
Norway's application to join the European Community, signalling a big
problem for Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, prime minister, as she seeks to turn
public opinion in favour of membership.
The most spectacular gains in the election yesterday were made by the
agrarian Centre party, which based its campaign on uncompromising opposition
to the EC.
Computer projections showed the party, led by Ms Anne Enger Lahnstein, more
than doubling its vote and overtaking the Conservative party as the largest
opposition group in the 165-member Storting (parliament).
The projections showed the Centre party, which won 11 seats in the last
election in 1989, increased its representation to 31, its best-ever result,
with 19 per cent of the vote. The Conservatives, meanwhile, suffered their
worst setback for 20 years, losing nine of 37 seats, with 15 per cent of the
vote. The right-wing Progress party, which supports EC membership, fell
sharply and was set to lose half its 22 seats.
'This is a demand from the people that we continue the fight against EC
membership,' said Ms Lahnstein, popularly known as the 'No Queen'.
Labour, with 37 per cent of the vote, was projected to win 67 seats, a gain
of four, due mainly to an improving economy and insistence that EC
membership will be decided by a referendum, not the election. Mrs Brundtland
said before the poll she would seek support on most issues except the EC
from the Socialist Left party or the Centre party. The Socialist Left, which
is anti-EC, was projected as losing four seats, to hold 13.
Final results were expected to be delayed because of a breakdown in the
computerised voting system in Oslo. Officials said a count from the capital
would not be completed until later today at the earliest, and another vote
might have to be called.
A senior Labour leader said a clear anti-EC result in the election would
harden the government's already tough stance in accession negotiations with
the Community begun earlier this year, particularly over the sensitive
issues of fishing and oil.
</TEXT>
