<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Tough line by Kohl in election warm-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Helmut Kohl yesterday spelt out law and order and economic
security as the twin themes of his campaign for re-election as German
chancellor next year.
In a broad-ranging restatement of his vision of a unified Germany in the
international community - anchored in the European Community and the Nato
alliance - he denounced the rise of right-wing violence as a threat to
Germany's internal order, as well as its international image.
At the same time he insisted that Germans should not be ashamed of asserting
their national identity within a united Europe. Patriotism must not be
abandoned as a preserve of the extremists, he warned.
In his keynote address to the annual conference of his Christian Democratic
Union, the principal party in the ruling German coalition, Mr Kohl hammered
home his other major election theme: the need for far-reaching reforms of
Germany's education system, working practices and social security, to ensure
the international competitiveness of the German economy.
It was a speech intended to appeal to the broad middle ground of German
politics, a denunciation of extremes in all their forms, and a thoughtful
analysis of the biggest challenges facing German society in the wake of
unification.
It contained by far the strongest denunciation he has yet voiced of
right-wing extremism, racist violence, and the rise of new neo-Nazi splinter
groups.
It was also an impressive restatement of Mr Kohl's conviction that German
unification and European unification are two sides of a single coin.
Yet it was not the rabble-rousing address at the start of a marathon
election year which the party faithful wanted.
It was a statesmanlike speech, not a party-political broadcast, and the
1,000 CDU delegates in Berlin's echoing international congress centre
received it politely but without obvious enthusiasm.
The Chancellor was undaunted. His popularity may be low, and he may fail to
inspire any standing ovations, but he is supremely confident of his position
as the architect of unification, as the dominant figure on the political
scene, and as the only chancellor-candidate the CDU has got.
'At a time of sweeping change, the people need direction and stability,' he
declared. 'The people want security. We are the ones who take their worries
seriously.'
He spelt out his firm commitment to the current ruling coalition - with the
Bavaria-based Christian Social Union and the liberal Free Democratic Party -
and by implication, a rejection of suggestions that a grand coalition with
the opposition Social Democrats would be preferable.
At a time of uncertainty, he implied, the voters would stick to the devil
they knew, and that meant Helmut Kohl as chancellor.
His vision of economic security did not mean 'fortress Germany,' he said.
It meant reform of Germany's entrenched labour practices and of its
excessively academic and over-long education system, to ensure
competitiveness.
He warned that financing of the social security and pensions system must be
reviewed to cope with an ageing population.
His emphasis on law and order is a clear response to voters' concerns,
currently driving the election campaign in Hamburg, where both the CDU and
SPD are fearful of a rise of the far right in next Sunday's poll.
For once, he pulled no punches in his condemnation of the extreme right.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
