<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Handshake seals Mideast deal: Jordan and Israel will today
agree on framework for peace and land negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Yitzhak Rabin and Mr Yassir Arafat yesterday sealed with a symbolic
handshake on the lawns of the White House the greatest breakthrough in the
Middle East conflict for 14 years, and pledged a new era of peace.
Yesterday's momentous occasion will be followed today with a declaration by
Jordan and Israel on the framework for peace talks.
The agenda provides for the first Israeli recognition of Jordanian claims to
land held by Israel. Similar agreements between Israel, Lebanon and Syria
are also under negotiation but are some way from conclusion, although all
parties at yesterday's signing are united in an effort to sustain the
momentum towards a comprehensive settlement.
The Israeli prime minister and the leader of the Palestine Liberation
Organisation, decades-long adversaries who met yesterday for the first time,
had watched in the brilliant morning sunshine as Mr Shimon Peres, Israel's
foreign minister, and Mr Mahmoud Abbas, the PLO executive committee member,
signed a short text outlining an agreement on limited Palestinian self-rule.
Both men signed two sets of documents, laid open on the 124-year-old table
on which Israel completed its first peace deal with a neighbour, Egypt, in
1979. The presidential author of that deal, the Camp David agreement, Mr
Jimmy Carter, looked on smiling from the front row of dignitaries seated on
the lawns.
'We who have fought against you, the Palestinians, we say to you in a loud
and clear voice - enough of blood and tears. Enough]' Mr Rabin declared to
applause after the signing, in a sombre speech that evoked the suffering of
Israelis throughout the Holocaust and over the decades of conflict with the
Palestinians. 'The time for peace has come.'
Mr Arafat, wearing a khaki military uniform and keffiyeh headdress, speaking
in Arabic, replied: 'My people are hoping that this agreement which we are
signing today marks the beginning of the end of a chapter of pain and
suffering which has lasted throughout this century.'
He said he hoped the outline agreement would 'usher in an age of peace,
co-existence and human rights'. After the signings, President Bill Clinton
shook the hands of both leaders, flanking him on the small pavilion built
for the signing.
A smiling Mr Arafat then offered his hand to Mr Rabin, who accepted it,
grave-faced, to a cheer from the previously hushed audience of 3,000 guests.
The Israeli prime minister had said before yesterday's signing that he would
shake hands with his former foe only 'if necessary'.
The rows of seated guests, some of whom had queued to enter the White House
from 7am for the 11am ceremony, included the entire US Congress, former US
presidents Mr Carter and Mr George Bush and scores of diplomats, lobbyists
and former foreign ministers who, in the words of Mr Warren Christopher, US
secretary of state, 'had toiled for decades in the search for peace in the
Middle East'.
Hundreds of yards away, beyond the White House garden railings, big crowds
of Jewish protesters, almost all wearing wide-brimmed black hats,
demonstrated throughout the ceremony, bearing posters saying 'Israel is in
danger' and 'Rabin resign'. A tiny clutch of Arab opponents to the peace
deal gathered a block away.
But there was little to trouble the low-key but intensive security ring
around the ceremony - the biggest open gathering of notables in Washington
since President Clinton's inauguration.
Mr Peres and Mr Abbas also emphasised the potentially historic nature of the
accord signed yesterday which, although only a declaration of understanding
to guide further negotiations, represents for the first time direct
negotiations between Israel and the main representatives of the Palestinian
people.
Mr Clinton, in a speech borrowing from both history and the scriptures,
thanked the many of those in the audience who had worked for decades for
just such a breakthrough as yesterday's. He said: 'A peace of the brave is
within our reach. Throughout the Middle East there is a great yearning for
the quiet miracle of a normal life.'
Mr Christopher added: 'This Israeli-Palestinian agreement cannot be
permitted to fail.' He pledged that the US 'will spare no effort to enable
the parties to turn agreements at the table to agreements on the ground'.
Mr Clinton offered specific thanks to the government of Norway, through
whose secret good offices the deal was hammered out.
After the euphoria of the ceremony, Mr Peres and Mr Rabin underlined the
difficulty of the task facing both sides. 'We are happy with the success, we
are not drunken with the estimation of what lies ahead of us,' Mr Peres told
reporters. He said both he and Mr Rabin were 'determined to continue and go
ahead' with the negotiations, but added: 'For the prime minister of Israel
today it was a most unusual challenge to penetrate the thickest
psychological wall in the Middle East. You must understand it. It wasn't
easy for him; it wasn't easy for me.'
Later, Mr Clinton held an unexpected private meeting with Mr Arafat during
which officials said he impressed on the PLO chairman the need to implement
the new agreement as swiftly as possible. According to an aide, Mr Clinton
made the point 'with some emphasis' that the Palestinians needed to 'seize
the moment'.
Mr Rabin and Mr Peres were expected to fly directly back to Jerusalem for
the start of the Jewish New Year festival. Mr Arafat stayed on to 'work'
Washington and was expected to attend more meetings today.
Israel and the PLO: special reports, Page 6
</TEXT>
