<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / International Company News: LTV plans share offer to help
reorganisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LTV, the third-biggest US steel producer, is planning an international share
offering just weeks after emerging from seven years in bankruptcy
protection.
The company plans to sell 20m new shares, 3m of them internationally,
according to a filing last week with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
Its share price fell Dollars  1/2 on the news, to end last week at Dollars
11.
LTV said it planned to use the proceeds to support its capital spending and
make contributions to its pension plan, among other things. As part of the
court-approved agreement with creditors that allowed it to emerge from
bankruptcy in June, LTV agreed to pay Dollars 850m into its pension fund at
once to cover part of the plan's Dollars 3bn underfunding. It has to pay the
remainder over the next 28 years.
The issue will be the second injection of capital for the steelmaker: its
financial reorganisation also triggered a Dollars 200m investment from
Sumitomo Metal Industries of Japan, which now holds around 10 per cent of
the company.
The share issue will be underwritten by Salomon Brothers, Goldman Sachs and
Smith Barney.
