FT  13 SEP 93 / Observer: Grub Street
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Observer is surprised to learn that the starting salary for a cook at the
New York Times' staff cafeteria, at Dollars 697 a week, is rather more than
that for a journalist at the FT's competitor, the Wall Street Journal.
This intriguing disparity has been uncovered by the Independent Association
of Publishers' Employees, the union which represents 2,000 employees at Dow
Jones, publishers of the Wall Street Journal.
The IAPE is negotiating a new three-year pay contract with Dow Jones
management.
It suggests the disparity between the cooks' and the reporters' salaries
supports its proposal to the company's shareholders that any increase in the
chief executive's remuneration package should be no more than that received
by employees.
