<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Directors attack EC policy on jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSTITUTE of Directors has launched a fresh attack against EC social
policy, describing it as a 'misdirected and damaging job-destroying
machine'.
In a submission to the European Commission the IoD says that the EC's social
chapter and social action programme are based on 'outdated and undemocratic
collectivist policies geared to the rights of organised labour and driven by
the self-interest of European trade unions'.
Mr Peter Morgan, IoD director-general, called for EC member countries to be
'set free from the shackles of social policy, which makes the labour market
inflexible and European business uncompetitive'.
Mr Morgan added: 'The biggest problem in Europe today is 17m unemployed. The
focus of future EC social and employment policy must be to get these people
back into work, an objective which will not be achieved by Europe's
anti-employment laws and an even heavier burden of regulation and social
cost on the job creators.'
The IoD's alternative charter concentrates on the rights and
responsibilities of the individual at work, rather than on collective
rights. Its proposals include performance-related pay and employee
involvement.
'The provisions of the charter would be left to national governments or
individual employers and employees to decide, free from Brussels diktat,' Mr
Morgan added.
The future of European Social Policy. IoD, 116 Pall Mall, London SW1Y 5ED.
Free.
</TEXT>
