<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Booksellers protest over HSE deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOOKSELLERS have appealed to the government to overturn a decision by the
Health and Safety Executive to sell its publications to a single bookshop
chain - Dillons.
In July the HSE announced that it had awarded the contract for the
distribution of both its free and priced publications to Promotional Logics
(Prolog), which will operate a warehouse and mail-order service, and Dillons
Bookstores, part of the Pentos group.
Mr Terry Collins, group chief executive of Blackwell, the Oxford bookseller,
has written to Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, asking him to 'call
in' the HSE decision for review.
At the moment HSE publications are available through Her Majesty's
Stationery Office, its 48 agents, and more than 3,000 bookshops throughout
the country.
From next month, critics say, essential publications such as Health and
Safety at Work regulations will be available in range and quantity only at
22 Dillons stores while a further 80 Dillons and 100 Ryman stores, also part
of Pentos, will act as order points.
In 15 main towns and cities such as Edinburgh, Norwich, Aberystwyth and
Stoke-on-Trent there will be no retail outlet where HSE publications can be
viewed and purchased.
Mr Collins told the employment secretary: 'To restrict availability at the
retail level to any government or government agency publications to a single
source runs contrary to the principles of open government.'
Mr Peter Rimmer, director of information of the HSE, has said the aim of the
new contract is to reduce distribution costs and to improve the marketing
and targeting of HSE publications. HMSO put in a bid for the contract but
was unsuccessful.
Any bookshop can buy the HSE publications at full price but only Prolog and
Dillons can buy at a discount.
</TEXT>
