<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Science foresight plan launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S ambitious 'technology foresight' programme, aimed at
picking areas on which the UK should concentrate research funding, will be
launched today.
Scientists, industrialists and civil servants are meeting in Edinburgh in
the first of a series of eight seminars to be held in different cities this
autumn. They will lay the foundations for the full-scale foresight exercise
next year.
Mr William Waldegrave, the minister for science, hopes that this will
involve several thousand people in science and business giving their views
and 'building a consensus on the most important generic technologies for the
future'.
The aim is to match the most promising scientific fields with the country's
research resources and UK companies willing and able to exploit the results
of the research. By 1995 the priorities identified in the foresight exercise
will start to influence the way the government allocates public spending of
about Pounds 5bn a year on research and development.
The technology foresight steering group, chaired by Professor William
Stewart, the government's chief scientific adviser, held its first meeting
last week.
Prof Stewart added that group had yet to decide about the technologies on
which to concentrate and the procedures that would be used for choosing
them.
Prof Howard Newby, chairman of the Economic and Social Research Council and
a member of the steering group, said: 'The most important objective in the
early stages must be to create a sense of common purpose between government,
industry and academics.'
</TEXT>
