<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Further sell-off protests expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT ministers yesterday sought to head off a fresh row about British
Rail privatisation by emphasising that the deep cuts in services planned in
BR's winter timetable were entirely separate from the privatisation plans.
Labour has called for a national protest campaign at the reduced services
revealed in the new timetable. Both Labour and the Liberal Democrats said
the cuts came as part of the approach to privatisation.
In spite of ministerial assurances, the reductions in weekend and off-peak
services will add to the difficulties the government faces next month when
parliament resumes discussion of the legislation to allow the private sector
to bid to run rail services.
Some of the leading Tory rebels are from constituencies in BR's Network
SouthEast area, seen by passenger organisations as one of the areas
particularly badly affected by the changes.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, insisted that the changes were part
of BR's normal management processes. 'This has got absolutely nothing to do
with privatisation,' he told BBC radio.
Mr MacGregor said that the service reductions arose because BR had carried
fewer passengers in the recession, leading to a fall in its revenue.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's transport spokesman, accused Mr MacGregor of
'monstrous cynicism' in cutting government funding for BR and predicted that
the issue would intensify the campaign against privatisation.
Mr Nick Harvey, Liberal Democrat transport spokesman, said: 'This confirms
all our worst fears - that to try to make the franchises more attractive to
private bidders, the whole public-service commitment is being slimmed down.
The regional railways have been warning for some time that the level of
funding the government was proposing for next year was going to mean massive
cuts.'
Mr Kenneth Carlisle, a former transport minister, is to lead a cross-party
delegation of MPs to meet Mr Roger Freeman, the transport minister, next
month to discuss rail services. He is the MP for Lincoln, one of the areas
worst hit by the cuts.
Tory MPs who rebelled when the privatisation legislation was debated in the
Commons earlier this year have already said that plans for substantial fare
increases would stiffen their determination to demand further concessions
from the government.
</TEXT>
