<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Cable revolution rumbles into the residential zones: The
established telecoms providers are facing stiff competition from new
operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNTIL RECENTLY most of us had no choice but to use British
Telecommunications at home. Mercury was something for business, and cable
companies were almost nowhere.
No longer. Mercury now has 375,000 domestic subscribers linked to its trunk
network. Cable companies, building local telephone networks across Britain's
urban areas, have signed up 164,000 residential customers - more than treble
the tally a year ago.
That is just the start. Most new phones have a blue button, giving direct
connection to Mercury for Pounds 11.75 a year. For those with old phones, a
new Mercury service will enable about half of all BT subscribers to use
Mercury by dialling 132 before their long-distance number. By the end of the
year '132' will be available in most areas with modern telephone exchanges.
Londoners can sign up now, and a marketing blitz is imminent.
As for cable, 14.5m homes are covered by franchises granted to companies to
build combined cable telephone and television networks. A total of 27
companies - 20 of them North American - have 127 franchises between them.
Networks are under construction in 62 areas and others will start later this
year. Virtually all cable subscribers have severed their BT connections,
relying for their long-distance calls on inter-connection agreements
negotiated by the cable companies, mostly with Mercury.
The sight of yet another outfit digging up the streets has not endeared the
cable companies to their potential customers. And once the roads are
re-surfaced many are reluctant to ask about the services for fear of
invasion by sales teams.
The salespeople come anyway. A day in the Portsmouth area, where Nynex, the
US-owned cable operator, is constructing one of its 18 networks, revealed a
high degree of enthusiasm for the new services. To Nynex's surprise, cable
telephone is proving more popular than cable television.
Nynex's team of 38 'cable advisers' are trudging the streets of Portsmouth
and its environs, armed with glossy brochures showing large savings on phone
bills and the benefits of 29 basic TV channels and another six premium
channels.
So far council estates have offered the richest pickings. On the city's Lee
Park estate take-up is more than 40 per cent. But it is significant across
the franchise area, which extends from Fareham in the west to Petersfield in
the north. A team out for a week in Fareham reported 27 per cent of homes
visited taking cable telephone, 25 per cent cable TV, and nearly 30 per cent
one or the other.
A few months after their initial foray the advisers go back to 're-market'.
One city area re-marketed in July was reporting total take-up of more than
38 per cent. Telephone was again the best seller, attracting 35 per cent of
homes visited compared with 32 per cent for cable TV. 'Without the advisers,
we'd get nowhere,' said Mr Karl Gross, managing director of the Nynex's
Solent franchise and a former Unilever executive. 'We need them to get over
people's hesitation that we're double-glazing merchants.'
The advisers are paid Pounds 70 a week. The rest is down to them, with
commissions paid not just on sales, but on everything including direct
debits, worth a pound each to them. An average sale earns an adviser Pounds
15.
One experienced hand said: 'It's not particularly hard-sell. You start with
the average 10 per cent off the phone bill, that always gets you a hearing.
Then you throw in the TV.' Once word has gone around, the job is far easier.
Those taking cable telephone were mainly concerned to save money. They
seemed to accept the glossy charts showing that they would save by switching
to Nynex - although some might be better off keeping their BT line using
Mercury for trunk calls (see table).
Few were worried about having to change their phone number. They wanted to
be assured about reliability and long-distance links. Mention of Nynex's US
experience and its connection to Mercury's long-distance network was enough
for most people. Surprisingly, BT seemed to be doing nothing in response,
apart from letters advertising its 'Option 15' discount rate.
Nynex's connection charge for TV is Pounds 35.99. An extra Pounds 20 (Pounds
15 for direct debit subscribers) gets you the phone too. The phone alone
comes for Pounds 60 (Pounds 55 with direct debit). Over 60s and the disabled
gain installation free, provided they take both the phone and TV. Perks
include itemised phone bills for all calls costing more than 20p. The
monthly telephone line rental is Pounds 6.45, with itemised billing for all
calls of more than 20p.
Portsmouth is Nynex's most advanced network, but Blackburn, Brighton,
Bromley, Derby, Bolton and north Surrey are progressing. The jewel in the
company's UK crown is Manchester, where work will start later this year. Mr
Eugene Connell, Nynex's UK director said: 'We plan to spend around Dollars
3bn in the UK over the next five years - our commitment is total.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
