<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Ernst &amp; Young raps accounts reform plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ERNST &amp; YOUNG, the UK's third largest accountancy firm, today launches an
outspoken attack on the Accounting Standards Board's plans to reform rules
governing financial reporting.
An Ernst &amp; Young report accuses the board, which sets accounting standards,
of heading in the wrong direction with its reforms, being overly academic,
ignoring its critics and diverging from international standards.
Ernst &amp; Young warns that the board threatens to sideline the traditional
concept of prudence in accounts.
The strongly worded criticism is one of the first public expressions of
discontent with the overall development of the new accounting standards
regime.
It is particularly significant because it was co-authored by Mr Ron
Paterson, a technical partner in the firm, who is a member of the board's
urgent issues task force.
Ernst &amp; Young's main concern is that the board is concentrating on the
so-called 'balance sheet approach' which focuses on attempting to value a
company's assets and liabilities regularly.
The firm argues that this is inaccurate and incompatible with a 'profit and
loss account approach' based on transactions - such as the sale of goods -
that have taken place and so can be measured with greater certainty. It
wants a return to 'historical cost' accounting, based on the value of an
asset at the time it was bought.
Mr David Tweedie, chairman of the Accounting Standards Board, said
yesterday: 'Most of what we are doing is just catching up with standards
elsewhere in the world.' The proposals would 'improve the balance sheet
without destroying the profit and loss account'. Ernst &amp; Young was 'in a
minority', with most users of accounts favouring regular revaluations on the
balance sheet and 70 per cent of British industry already doing so, he said.
Until now there has been a delicate consensus, with few companies and no
accounting firms speaking out directly against the board's reform programme.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ernst and Young.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
