<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / The black anniversary turns golden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS Thursday marks the anniversary of Black Wednesday. It has been 12
months in which the UK economy has enjoyed a golden period - at least in
comparison with what went before. Sterling's exit from the European exchange
rate mechanism on September 16 was a big factor behind the 1.3 per cent
growth in gross domestic product between the third quarter of 1992 and the
second quarter this year, writes Peter Marsh.
Coming after the deep recession which started during 1990 and petered out
around the middle of last year, such a large expansion in output would
almost certainly not have happened had the pound stayed in the mechanism.
Sterling's decoupling from the D-Mark has enabled the UK government to cut
interest rates from 10 per cent to 6 per cent, boosting domestic demand.
That particularly helped manufacturers, which have pushed up output 2.6 per
cent in the past year. They have been aided by the 11 per cent depreciation
in sterling (on a trade-weighted basis) over the period which has increased
competitiveness.
And while unemployment remains high, it has come down from a record 2.99m in
January.
</TEXT>
