<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Businesses seek easier financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 20-POINT programme to make it easier for small and medium-sized companies
to obtain finance during the hoped-for economic recovery will be unveiled to
the Treasury this week by the Association of Independent Businesses, a lobby
group.
The ideas from the association, representing about 12,000 companies, will
feed into a six-month study by the Treasury into whether 'market
imperfections' distort the flow of cash into industry and so impede growth.
The suggestions include putting greater pressure on banks to fund small
companies, and tax changes to release more cash for industrial investment.
They will be relayed at a meeting on Wednesday between the association and
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury. Mr Dorrell is
expected to discuss the proposals with Mr Anthony Nelson, Treasury economic
secretary, who is in charge of the funding inquiry.
Mr Toby Aykroyd, director of operations at the association, welcomed the
Treasury study. He said it was important to lay the ground for 'medium-term
reforms' in the financing of small companies.
He said new ideas to help the sector might be needed, especially during the
expected upturn over the next year or so.
The meeting with Mr Dorrell was set up before last week's announcement of
the Treasury study, which will be based on a series of visits by Mr Nelson
to small companies around Britain. Mr Nelson will also talk to City
institutions and banks to discuss funding problems.
Proposals from the association include:
Persuading banks to give more information about their loans to small
companies, including those made under the government's loan guarantee
scheme, so that lobbying groups can better assess the banks' record in this
area.
Revamping of the business expansion scheme to provide tax advantages for
companies and individuals when investing in small companies.
Extra capital allowances to enable small companies to claim tax relief
against investments.
Increased grants to reduce burden of business rates. Extensions in schemes
to enable small companies to offset financial losses against tax on later
profits.
The study by Mr Nelson follows efforts by the Treasury over the past year to
form a better understanding of business issues. The inquiry was welcomed by
the Confederation of British Industry and the Institute of Directors. Mr
Stan Mendham, founder of the 21,000-member Forum of Private Businesses, said
funding of small companies was 'monumentally important' to the UK's economic
health.
</TEXT>
