<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / West End offices go to French for Pounds 62m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO FRENCH insurance companies have paid Pounds 62.5m for an office building
in London's St James's Square, in one of the largest West End property
transactions this year.
The deal illustrates the prominence of overseas investors in the UK property
market, resulting from the devaluation of sterling, the reduction in UK
interest rates and the opportunity to buy properties at historically high
yields.
Foreign buyers are likely to spend about Pounds 1.75bn on UK property this
year, compared with Pounds 1.33bn in 1992, says a report by DTZ Debenham
Thorpe, property advisers.
The building at 20 St James's Square has been acquired by GAN and UAP, two
of France's largest insurance companies, from Kumagai Gumi, the Japanese
developer, on a yield of just under 7.5 per cent.
The 70,000 sq ft offices - occupied by Grand Metropolitan, the food, drinks
and retailing group - generates an income of Pounds 4.75m a year from one of
the highest rents in London. Grand Metropolitan has a 25-year lease, agreed
in 1990.
DTZ Debenham Thorpe says demand for UK property is the highest for at least
five years. UK financial institutions are preparing to invest more than
Pounds 7bn in the next 12 to 18 months as money flows back into commercial
property.
Overseas investment in UK property totalled Pounds 837m for the first half
of this year, according to DTZ - about the same level as the last six months
of last year.
Hong Kong and Chinese investors have been the most prominent source of
demand, accounting for nearly a quarter of investment so far this year.
Investors from the Far East have spent Pounds 195m for the first half of
this year, compared with a total of Pounds 63m last year.
Money into Property. Research Division, DTZ Debenham Thorpe, 44 Brook
Street, London W1A 4AG. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
