<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Holst's victorious Mideast role boosts Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Johan Joergen Holst, Norway's foreign minister and chief mediator in
secret Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations, has boosted the Labour
party's standing ahead of already certain victory in today's general
election.
Heralded as a national hero for his contribution to the Middle East peace
agreement, Mr Holst yesterday campaigned before an enthusiastic crowd under
blue skies in Hoenefoss, a small town north-west of Oslo. He was accompanied
by his four-year-old son Edvard, who has also become a mini-hero in the eyes
of Norwegians who have listened as the father and son duo broadcast across
international airwaves almost continually in recent days as the story of
Oslo's role in the Middle East peace process unfolded.
Between signing autographs, Mr Holst called on the electorate to vote Labour
so the 'steady course' of his party's policies could be continued. 'This is
not the time for Norway to be subjected to the experimental policies of
other parties,' he warned.
According to a poll published yesterday, support for Labour is holding
steady at 34.8 per cent, while the main opposition Conservative party
weakened to 18.1 per cent from 22.2 in the 1989 general election.
Analysts say the importance of the Conservative party's strong defence
platform has dimmed in the eyes of an electorate no longer preoccupied with
defence and security issues.
The anti-EC agrarian Centre party, set to become the other victor in today's
election, polled 16.1 per cent against a 6.5 per cent vote in 1989,
indicating support from an electorate ever-resistant to EC membership.
One of the most striking features of yesterday's poll is the plunge in
support to 6.6 per cent for the populist right-wing Progress party, from 13
per cent in 1989. However, on Saturday in Oslo's main streets, Mr Carl
Hagen, the leader of Progress, drew a large crowd from the public who had
turned out to hear the last-minute pleas for support from the numerous
parties.
Standing on a wobbly folding table, an ever-confident Mr Hagen warned the
crowd that endorsing Labour's 'steady course' meant continued health queues,
record unemployment, and persistent rises in the budget deficit which would
have to be paid for by their children.
</TEXT>
