<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Lowest ranks take brunt of cuts in UK armed services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFFICERS have escaped largely unscathed from cuts in the UK armed forces
over the past decade, which have concentrated on the lowest ranks, according
to official figures.
The number of army privates and their equivalents in the navy and air force
fell by more than a quarter between 1980 and 1992. Officer numbers fell by
just 1.6 per cent over the same period. The number of colonels and
lieutenant-colonels rose.
Overall, the strength of the armed services fell by 36,891 between 1980 and
1992. But nine out of 10 of those were privates; the number of commissioned
officers fell by just 630.
The number of officers at the rank of major-general and above fell by 21 per
cent, but the reductions in the number of other officers were small by
comparison.
A similar pattern can be seen among the 87,900 white-collar civilian staff
employed by the Ministry of Defence. Their numbers have fallen by a quarter
since 1980, but there has been no reduction in the number of middle and
senior managers.
The distribution of cuts was described as 'surprising' by Professor Paul
Rogers, a defence expert at Bradford University.
Under the last Labour government, there were substantial cuts at all ranks
of officers. Between 1975 and 1980, the number of servicemen to each officer
rose from 6.26 to 6.71.
Since 1980, however, the number of servicemen per officer has fallen. After
14 years of Conservative government, there are now 5.89 servicemen to each
officer.
Over the same period, officers' pay rose by more than 170 per cent, while
the pay of privates rose 138 per cent. A general now typically earns almost
nine times the pay of a private, compared with seven times in 1980.
The policy of getting rid of privates rather than officers, combined with
widening pay differentials, has reduced the savings from manpower cuts. The
proportion of the defence budget spent on pay rose from 36 per cent in 1985
to almost 42 per cent this year, while the proportion spent on equipment has
fallen.
Dr David Clark, Labour's defence spokesman, said the UK needed 'more
ordinary squaddies for deployment on peacekeeping duties in places like
Bosnia'. Officers found it all too easy to fill discharge lists with other
ranks, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
