<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / US pledges key role in push for wider settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US promised to take a central political, financial and even military
role in efforts to sustain the momentum for a wider Middle East peace
yesterday on the eve of the accord between Israel and the Palestinian
Liberation Organisation.
At 11am today, Mr Yassir Arafat, the PLO leader, and Mr Yitzhak Rabin,
Israel's prime minister, will stand together on the White House south lawn
to witness signature of an outline agreement giving Palestinians limited
self-rule in the territories occupied by Israel in the 1967 war.
A short text, the fruit of months of secret negotiations in Norway, is
intended to mark the end of one of the 20th century's most bitter conflicts.
It will be signed by Mr Shimon Peres, the Israeli foreign minister, and Mr
Abu Mazen, a senior Palestine Liberation Organisation official, before 2,500
distinguished guests.
The hour-long ceremony offers the prospect of Mr Arafat and Mr Rabin, sworn
foes for decades, endorsing the peace with a symbolic handshake.
Mr Arafat, who flew into Washington last night for his first visit to the US
since he brandished both a gun and an olive branch at the United Nations in
1974, is expected to forsake his customary military fatigues and pistol and
don a suit.
The ceremony will cap an extraordinary two weeks which began when Israel and
the PLO surprised the world by announcing they were on the verge of an
agreement on mutual recognition and limited Palestinian autonomy. In a
series of statements yesterday, the Clinton administration strove to
maintain efforts for a wider peace with undertakings designed to accelerate
agreement between Israel and its other Arab neighbours - Jordan, Syria and
Lebanon.
In an interview with the New York Times, President Bill Clinton assured
Israel that the peace accord with the PLO would not herald cuts in billions
of dollars of aid and military assistance. Mr Warren Christopher, the
secretary of state, also said that the US was prepared to offer troops to
guarantee security in the Golan Heights after any negotiated Israeli
withdrawal.
But Mr Clinton and Mr Al Gore, his vice-president, also stressed that while
the US was prepared to offer financial aid to support peace in the region,
it did not see itself as the main provider. 'We stand ready to do our part,'
Mr Gore said on NBC television. 'But we're not speaking of anything
comparable to previous agreements where the US was the sole guarantor.'
Mr Clinton echoed the point when he announced that he had won an undertaking
from King Fahd, the Saudi Arabian ruler, for a strong Saudi-led aid package
from the Gulf states - whose relations with the Palestinians were deeply
soured by the PLO's pro-Iraqi stand in the Gulf war. Mr Clinton quoted the
king as saying: 'You take the lead in organising it, and tell us what we are
supposed to do.'
The president also said he had elicited approval for the PLO-Israeli deal
from President Hafez al-Assad, the Syrian leader, who had hitherto refrained
from any direct comment on the agreement. Quoting also from a recent
30-minute conversation with Mr Assad, Mr Clinton said the Syrian leader
said: 'It is a positive thing, this agreement, for all of us.'
Mr Clinton said Mr Assad explicity called on the US to play a continuing and
central role in mediating an agreement between Israel and Syria, which
hinges on an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights in return for a
Syrian declaration of 'full peace' with Tel Aviv.
</TEXT>
<XX>
