<HEADLINE>
FT  13 SEP 93 / Bus drivers find route to fortune
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SELECT group of bus drivers will make a profit of more than Pounds 100,000
each through the forthcoming flotation of Badgerline Group, the Avon-based
company that has grown into one of the UK's biggest providers of local bus
services.
The company, which operates 2,300 buses and coaches in Midlands, south Wales
and the south of England, will be floated on the stock market in November
with an estimated value of Pounds 100m.
The original 80 employees who took shares seven years ago when the company
was created by a management led buy-out, have seen the value of their stake
increase nearly a hundredfold. They will gain even more when the terms of
the flotation are finalised, while some modestly paid middle managers will
have shares worth more than Pounds 200,000.
The company set out on its route to fortune in 1986 when a group of managers
and employees succeeded with a Pounds 3m buy-out of Badgerline, the third of
the National Bus Company's subsidiaries to be sold in the government's
privatisation programme.
A report by the National Audit Office said that one in four of the
state-owned bus companies was sold for less than the value of its vehicles
and properties.
The price paid in the Badgerline buy-out, completed before deregulation of
bus services, reflected the 'reasonable commercial risk' involved, said Mr
Trevor Smallwood, its chairman.
Takeover trail, Page 20
</TEXT>
